00:46.647 --> 00:49.617
Good evening,
and welcome to "Montague."

00:49.650 --> 00:51.885
I'm your host,
Franklin Montague.

00:51.919 --> 00:53.387
And today we're gonna
take a look

00:53.421 --> 00:55.889
at the growing outlook
of accepted sexuality

00:55.923 --> 00:58.292
and its effects
on black youth and culture.

00:58.326 --> 00:59.927
With us today, we have

00:59.960 --> 01:02.696
the Head of the Center
of Trans-American Issues,

01:02.730 --> 01:04.198
Dr. Debra Holt,

01:04.232 --> 01:06.734
and recording artist
Paper Boi.

01:06.767 --> 01:08.369
Good evening to you both.

01:08.402 --> 01:09.770
-Good evening, Montague.
-'Sup?

01:09.803 --> 01:11.372
Uh, let's start
at the beginning.

01:11.405 --> 01:14.442
Paper Boi, last Tuesday
you engaged in a Twitter rant

01:14.475 --> 01:17.278
that had some pretty
inflammatory statements.

01:17.311 --> 01:19.079
But the one statement
that seems to have made

01:19.113 --> 01:20.714
-the biggest impact...
-(sighs)

01:20.748 --> 01:22.750
Was this one and I quote,
"Y'all the..."

01:22.783 --> 01:26.654
N-words "who said I was weird
for not wanting to"

01:26.687 --> 01:29.056
F-word "Caitlyn Jenner."

01:29.089 --> 01:31.892
Would you want to, uh,
explain that statement?

01:31.925 --> 01:33.961
No.

01:35.796 --> 01:39.900
Well, could you
explain that statement?

01:39.933 --> 01:42.236
(blows)
I...

01:42.270 --> 01:43.904
meant what I said.

01:43.937 --> 01:47.275
You don't think
your tweets are transphobic?

01:47.308 --> 01:48.809
I just don't have to
have sex

01:48.842 --> 01:50.311
with Caitlyn Jenner
'cause y'all say so.

01:50.344 --> 01:52.112
Mm.
So you don't think

01:52.146 --> 01:53.847
-Caitlyn Jenner's important?
-(tsks)

01:53.881 --> 01:55.349
Look, I get what
y'all saying, right?

01:55.383 --> 01:58.085
But she's not
super important to me,

01:58.118 --> 01:59.653
like, not my life.

01:59.687 --> 02:03.090
So how long
have you disliked transpeople?

02:03.123 --> 02:05.326
Man, look,
I just found out they exist,

02:05.359 --> 02:06.927
-to be honest.
-I--No, no--

02:06.960 --> 02:09.029
"I make her switch sides,
Caitlyn Jenner in reverse"?

02:09.062 --> 02:10.964
Is that not a--
a lyric of yours?

02:10.998 --> 02:12.500
Man, I was just rapping, man.

02:12.533 --> 02:14.435
Look, I've said worse things.

02:14.468 --> 02:16.770
You ever heard my song,
"Illuminati Sex"?

02:16.804 --> 02:18.372
-Haven't heard it yet.
-Well, there we go then.

02:18.406 --> 02:20.174
Debra, you've written

02:20.208 --> 02:22.376
about this current phenomenon
in your book,

02:22.410 --> 02:25.179
Transition:
Gender in a New Generation.

02:25.213 --> 02:27.448
What do you think
about all this?

02:27.481 --> 02:29.350
I look at these statements as

02:29.383 --> 02:31.319
natural consequences
of a culture

02:31.352 --> 02:33.120
-of exclusion and power.
-Mm.

02:33.153 --> 02:34.622
You know, there's--
there's a large swath of...

02:34.655 --> 02:36.824
-(scoffs)
-Gender and sexuality roles

02:36.857 --> 02:39.793
that are just being exposed to
a large portion of the public.

02:39.827 --> 02:41.362
(chuckling)

02:41.395 --> 02:43.464
DEBRA: Uh, it's harder
for certain sections

02:43.497 --> 02:44.998
to deal with this transition

02:45.032 --> 02:47.235
uh, because of conflict
of interest,

02:47.268 --> 02:49.837
and, frankly, identity issues.

02:49.870 --> 02:51.539
In this case,
the rap community.

02:51.572 --> 02:53.541
Now, I truly believe
it's, uh,

02:53.574 --> 02:55.909
has more to do with issues
of masculinity

02:55.943 --> 02:58.312
in the black community
than actual

02:58.346 --> 03:00.414
homophobia or--or transphobia.

03:00.448 --> 03:02.350
-Please explain.
-Yes, please, please.

03:02.383 --> 03:04.051
Tell me--
tell me about myself.

03:04.084 --> 03:05.653
Go on.

03:05.686 --> 03:08.256
Well, Mis--Mister, uh, Pa--
Mr. Paper Boi--

03:08.289 --> 03:09.557
Mister, yeah.

03:09.590 --> 03:12.159
What would you
consider yourself?

03:12.192 --> 03:13.327
A rapper?

03:13.361 --> 03:14.395
A straight rapper?

03:14.428 --> 03:15.863
Hell yeah.

03:15.896 --> 03:17.531
Well, I did some research
on your lyrics,

03:17.565 --> 03:20.100
and they're actually
very pro sexual-spectrum.

03:20.133 --> 03:21.435
-Oh?
-Pro-what?

03:21.469 --> 03:23.737
"If I eff with you,
you my N-word,

03:23.771 --> 03:25.205
you my N-word for life."

03:25.239 --> 03:26.607
Yo, you know
that ain't what I meant.

03:26.640 --> 03:27.875
Yeah, oh, I understand,
but, you know,

03:27.908 --> 03:29.343
there's a layer of fluidity...

03:29.377 --> 03:30.878
No, no, no.
There's no extra layer.

03:30.911 --> 03:32.746
DEBRA: That you yourself
don't even realize.

03:32.780 --> 03:34.348
I don't think about
what I'm rapping half the time.

03:34.382 --> 03:35.416
Look, I'm just trying
to get paid,

03:35.449 --> 03:36.750
you feel me?
Look, (bleep),

03:36.784 --> 03:38.519
why you think
I'm on this show?

03:38.552 --> 03:41.589
You're not
getting paid for this.

03:41.622 --> 03:43.924
Hey--
Hey, Earn--man?

03:43.957 --> 03:46.560
Black men aren't ready
to accept the implications

03:46.594 --> 03:48.296
of a trans-accepting culture.

03:48.329 --> 03:50.097
No--look, I'm allowed
to say that it's weird.

03:50.130 --> 03:51.599
"It"?

03:51.632 --> 03:52.966
No, look, I'm not
calling him a "it."

03:53.000 --> 03:54.368
-Naw, I'm just saying that--
-"Him"?

03:54.402 --> 03:55.903
Look--look, can I say something?
Damn!

03:55.936 --> 03:57.438
FRANKLIN: All right.
-Well, it depends.

03:57.471 --> 03:59.139
-I was trying to say--
-We got to take a break.

03:59.172 --> 04:00.774
When we're back,
we're gonna take a look

04:00.808 --> 04:03.644
